eft:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Who we are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some key principles relating to taxation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the main poi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nts we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">think are important for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Welsh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tax proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How the CIOT can contribute</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Probably the key point we would wish to make is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">developing fully operational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">devolv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed taxes will take considerable time and resources. That may seem an obvious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">point but the timescales involved and the resources needed must not be underestimated.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Chartered Institute of Taxation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIOT is the leading professional body in the United Kingdom concerned solely with taxation. The CIOT is an educational charit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y, promoting education and study of the administration and practice of taxation. One of our key aims is to work for a better, more efficient, tax system for all affected by it – taxpayers, their advisers and the authorities. The CIOT’s work covers all aspe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cts of taxation, including direct and indirect taxes and duties. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIOT draws on our members’ experience in private practice, commerce and industry, government and academia to improve tax administration and propose and explain how tax policy objectives can most effectively be achieved. We also link to, and draw on, si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">milar leading professional tax bodies in other countries. The CIOT’s comments and recommendations on tax issues are made in line with our charitable objectives: we are politically neutral in our work.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIOT’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">17,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> members have the practising title of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘Chartered Tax Adviser’ and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">designatory</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> letters ‘CTA’, to represent the leading tax qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The Low Incomes Tax Reform Group</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through our Low Incomes Tax Reform Group (LITRG), the CIOT has a particular focus on improving the tax system, includ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing tax credits and benefits, for the unrepresented taxpayer. LITRG is an initiative of the CIOT to give </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a voice to the unrepresented, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those who cannot afford to take professional advice. Since 1998 LITRG has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to improve the policy and proce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sses of the tax, tax credits and associated welfare systems for the benefit of those on low incomes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Key principles for taxation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Welsh Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has a real opportunity to design the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">devolved taxes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in line with proper principles. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We think the Welsh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Affairs Committee could usefully emphasise the importance of these principles in its report.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">think there are four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> key principles to be borne in mind in the design of tax systems:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Simplicity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Consultation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are firm believers in the benefits of proper consultation. The point is to get practical input into the development of new tax law. More subtly, a key benefit is that consultation will make taxpayers and advisers more supportive of the law if they have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been involved with its development. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are very supportive of the UK Government’s framework for tax consultations as set out in ‘Tax Policy Making: a new approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Its principles parallel our views on what makes effective consultation, views we have pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t forward many times over the years:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consult in stages (principles, then direction, then detail)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Proper evaluation of input and good feedback</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All carried out over a proper timescale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Only consult if there is a real chance of change – a willingness t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o listen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The guiding principle must be that all tax policy changes are consulted on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main exception would be changes in tax rates. We do accept that changes in rates are always going to be a matter for government and would not normally be susceptible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to consultation, though there have been instances where the implications of what seemed to be rate changes would have emerged with consultation</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would be happy to supply fuller comments about consultation, including reflections on our experience of the consultative process, if that were helpful. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Stability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A stable tax system – one that changes only when it needs to – is an important part of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e business environment. Investment is encouraged if businesses have confidence in the way the returns from their investment will be taxed. One of the conclusions of the Office of Tax Simplific</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation’s (OTS) first project on small b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">usiness</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was that the grea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">test source of complexity for small business is change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ideally taxes should be underpinned by a proper framework – key aims for the tax and principles under which it will operate. For the government, the overriding point is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to promote confidence in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tax system. That delivers benefits as taxpayers (business and individual) are more likely to comply with their responsibilities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Certainty</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stability promotes certainty and many businesses put certainty at the top of their list of what a tax system needs t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o deliver. They want to know what the result of their actions will be in tax terms. For this reason, retrospective changes to tax laws are very damaging and should be avoided: another benefit of consultation, to ‘get it right first time’.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One manifestatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n of certainty is that taxes should be laid down clearly in statute. In today’s complex environment, guidance notes by the tax authority will often be necessary, particularly for the unrepresented. But such material should be explanations, assistance and g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uidance, not a way for the tax authority to interpret (or even worse, change) the law to how it thinks it should operate. Citizens should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e taxed by law, not by guidance,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> nor untaxed by concession.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Simplicity</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Taxes should as far as possible be expressed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in clear law and be simple to operate. Administrative burdens on taxpayers should be minimised. When developing new tax laws, it should be part of the planning process to develop the necessary compliance routines and draft the relevant forms to test out th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e likely burdens that will be imposed and how easy it will be to comply. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should be borne in mind that it can be more cost-effective in some cases for the central authority to carry out aspects of the administration on a central basis, rather than devo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lve the work to taxpayers. That said, we accept that in transaction taxes, those taxpayers who are liable should expect to shoulder most of the compliance burden.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One issue to consider under this heading is the place of digital procedures. In general we s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">upport the idea of ‘digital by default’: that in today’s environment, digital communication (e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">filing, online intelligent forms, information being available on line etc) should be the norm. But it should not be compulsory: regard must be had to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘digitally excluded’. LITRG has a particular interest in this area</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is not solely an issue for individuals; many small businesses still rely on ‘traditional’ methods. In developing tax laws, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Welsh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Government needs to have regard to how these grou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ps should be catered for. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Some comments on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Welsh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tax proposals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A substantial part of the draft Wales Bill covers taxation powers. The taxes to be devolved to the Welsh Government are as devolved to Scotland and follow from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Silk Commission proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The CIOT made submissions to the Silk Commission and we support the ways in which these proposals have been developed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Welsh rate of income tax</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The decision to allow the Welsh Government a single rate of income tax rather than the varied rates as sugge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sted by the Silk report introduces the same system as in Scotland. Although this is clearly a very important matter of principle, we think the real work now has to start in terms of how the tax will actually be managed and collected. From our work over the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Scottish rate of income tax (SRIT), we think that key issues are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Who runs the system: is this to be HM Revenue &amp; Customs, as with SRIT?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Who is a Welsh taxpayer?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What is income for the purposes of the Welsh tax rate?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How to ensure those affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">understand the implications?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How to minimise administrative burdens?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals in new s116D-G of the Governance of Wales Act 2006 parallel the equivalent Scottish provisions for defining who is liable to the new tax and correctly build on the new UK S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tatutory Residence Test. The aim has to be that the vast majority of people can easily ascertain whether they will be Welsh taxpayers (or not) and are sure of their position. Work will be needed over practical issues, such as people who travel regularly be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tween Wales and Eng</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">land for work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has been constructive engagement with HMRC over various technical matters relating to SRIT.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Not all are fully resolved. Examples include tax relief for pension contributions and gift aid donations, and such matters as PAYE settlement agreements. We think it is important that rules and practices for the Welsh and Scottish rates on income tax are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in step: it would be administratively inefficient – as well as confusing for some taxpayers and employers – if there were definitional differences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A major issue that needs to be tackled is that of communication: making sure the right messages are convey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed to taxpayers. Taxpayers may easily have a variety of misconceptions about the implications of the new tax system. As implementation approaches, there needs to be a carefully designed programme of communication to taxpayers explaining who is affected, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eir responsi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bilities and the implications, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plus of course how to get additional help and explanations. This will need proper resourcing.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have regularly pointed out the need to consider demands on employers (and pension providers)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in tax changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">example is the extent to which employers will need to give information about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Welsh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tax on payslips: the point being that plenty of time needs to be allowed for employers and software suppliers to develop necessary systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It needs to be borne in mind that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it will not just be Welsh businesses that will have to operate the Welsh rate of income tax.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Devolving Stamp Duty Land Tax</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consideration should be given to adopting a progressive rate system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the successor Welsh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tax to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> remove the market distortions c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reated by the current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SDLT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘slab’ system. In the context of the residential property market, the effect of the SDLT ‘slab’ system (under which the rate of SDLT applies to the whole consideration once a threshold is reached) is widely recognised as creating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> market distortions with bunching around the price thresholds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and creating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> avoidance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (see the case of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Orsman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> v HMRC</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2012, where an allocation of just £800 to garage fittings was enough to reduce the SDLT by £5,200)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to minimise uncertainty, particularly in the commercial property market, it is important that any inevitable uncertainty over likely future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">design and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rates of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the new tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is kept to a minimum. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This includes the approach to anti-avoidance rules wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ere there will need to be a balance struck between the desire to guard against avoidance and creating complex rules and uncertainty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Delays in doing so may lead to investment decisions being delayed or directed elsewhere.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are challenging and problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">atic aspects of SDLT such as the provisions relating to leases, partnerships and trusts. In designing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the new tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re is a clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunity to consult on simplifying the complex aspects of SDLT. We think it is important that sufficient time is built in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the legislative timetable to allow for consultation. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he current SDLT online return is overly complex and inflexible to change. Registers of Scotland are currently developing a simplified online Land and Buildings Transaction Tax return. The Welsh Gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ernment may wish to consider a similar approach. Irrespective of the arrangements adopte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for collection of devolved taxes, the costs of administration, at least in the longer term, should be reduced if the Welsh Government can construct a less complex tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> than its SDLT predecessor with a simplified online return.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Welsh Landfill tax</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">28</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A key aim must be to tax what is actually discarded into landfill, not simply what enters the site. The tax structure needs to encourage recycling.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Revenue Wales and a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Tax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Management Bill</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">29</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A significant matter is how the new taxes are run: a separate tax authority or by HMRC as agent for the Welsh Government. We assume the former will be the case, thus an organisation parallel to Revenue Scotland will need to be established.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> That will take time and resource.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">30</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re will also be a need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">develop a taxes management system that can cover all the taxes likely to be devolved to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Ideally tax management provisions should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be common across all taxes, with difference only where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the nature of the tax requires differences.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How the CIOT can contribute</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">31</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Both the CIOT and LITRG operate across the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with an extensive and active branch network including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> South Wales Branch. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We employ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a number of Technical Officers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who coordinate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and distil input from around 300 of our members who volunteer their time on our various technical committees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many more of our members volunteer their time to help with Education, Branches and Professional Standards activities. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">32</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our contributions to consu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ltations and general discussions therefore draw on the knowledge and experience of both our members in practice and the in-house technical team. With LITRG we have many links to wider groups who have an interest in tax matters. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">33</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIOT has had significa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt involvement with the development of the Scottish tax system and would be able to draw on that experience in contributing to the development of Welsh tax proposals. Submissions that we have made on Scottish tax proposals have regularly drawn on surveys o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f our members in practice in Scotland. We have also used mediums such as round tables, conference sessions, webinars and articles in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Tax Adviser </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">magazine to disseminate information and discuss issues. We would be pleased to work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Welsh Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o make use of these avenues to discuss tax matters, particularly around practical implications of proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">20 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/d/junebudget_tax_policy_making.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/d/junebudget_tax_policy_making.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> , published 1 June 2010; with response documents and further comments published 9 December 2010 at </span><a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/tax_policy_making_new_approach.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/tax_policy_making_new_approach.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> An e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">xample would be the changes to CGT Rates in the summer 2010 Budget. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> See </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/small-business-tax-review"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt